Terasology is designed to be a modular voxel engine, capable of much more than simply a sandbox style gameplay. This project aims at adding an additional gameplay template to the lineup, to show off the capabilities of Terasology. The template is not simply a demonstration of this and is also to be a fully playable and fun gamemode.

This GSoC project intends to deliver a fully functioning Tower Defence gameplay experience. This experience will utilise the voxel engine capabilities of Terasology to provide some interesting and unique functionality.
The gameplay itself is broken up into major milestones. These are intended to be short points, with expanded information in the detailed design section towards the end of the document.
A circular flat playing field
Three entrances on the outer rim
A goal in the centre
A modifiable field in the rest of it
Enemies that travel directly towards the goal, inflicting damage if they reach it
They navigate along the shortest path through the main field
They don't attack any towers
That drop the currency, Scrap
Towers that can be placed anywhere in the world and that damage the enemies
Blocks enemy paths so they take a different route
Can inflict effects other than pure damage
Can be upgraded by replacing blocks with more advanced versions.
Built from multiple blocks by the player
Two phases, where the focus is shifted between Building and Defending.
In the building phase the enemy path is shown and build times are 0
In the defending phase actions have a build time
The player
Has an shop inventory where the currency is dropped by enemies, Scrap
Still bound by the regular physical rules of Terasology.
A status screen which displays important wave and enemy information
Also includes a minimap, a wave progression bar and a goal health bar as HUD items
Displays a summary of the next waves, the enemies in them and other important status information
Gameplay template that is fully supported and integrated
Is available from the drop down menu when the module is enabled
Does not require a specific save file to be loaded (ala Lost)
Fully standalone but also supports as many other modules as possible
Documentation and guides on the content
Developer focused docs should be on the repo
Player focused docs in the repo and in game. 
Stretch Goals
The base concept is one that can be expanded very easily to include more features or to expand existing ones. If any of these goals are possible do complete during GSoC, this will become apparent early on. If this happens I will discuss with my mentor and decide if I will add on such a thing
Player based combat
Player has linked health with goal
Enemies will attack either player or goal (based on distance)
Player can fight back with weapons
Supplements tower based combat, does not replace it
Multiple defence fields in the world.
Have other tower defense fields placed into the world
When one is beaten, another is revealed and can be played
Each field has different base layout that allows for a more challenging system, for instance, sections that may be multiple levels
Multiplayer Co-op
Have two or more players work in tandem to defend the goal.
More players would mean more enemies and more difficulty
Multiplayer PvP
Implement a system whereby players have their own tower defense bases
Can send hordes to attack other bases or to assist other bases.
Rather ambitious and potentially even worthy of it's own GSoC if expanded.

As the milestones simply provide a brief dot point form of the feature set, this section goes into much greater detail. It is also accompanied by a following technical details section which briefly explains the expected implementation method.

Infrastructure
In order to make the gameplay template as easy to use a possible it should only require the main module being activated and then the template selected from the drop-down list. It shouldn't rely on any techniques used by other templates such as building everything into a save file and then distributing that save file, such as is done by Lost.
Another key point that is more applicable to the stretch goals is to have the template be compatible with as many modules as possible. This means things like for the stretch goal of having the player in combat, items should be usable from a different Equipment module if it is activated. Or in the case of the expanded world goal, compatible with custom world generations.
The Playing Field
The game field consists of a goal at the centre of a flat circular area. At the start of each wave, enemies will enter from three points on the outer circumference. These entrances remain the same each wave, although varying amounts of enemies will use each entrance.
In the mockup, the red line is the path the enemies are taking and the orange sections are the entrances. The goal is at the centre and along the path are the player built towers in green. Each pixel in the image is one block.

Initially the area will be filled with random segments of basic walls. These segments will provide the basis for the maze-like structure of the field. These initial walls can be removed by the player as any other wall. The player can alter the field by placing their own walls or towers, which are outlined below. 
The walls and towers serve to direct the enemies into specific paths. This allows the player to predict and manipulate the enemy’s movements. There are exceptions to this rule and other specific edge cases that are discussed in the enemy section.
To facilitate the player being able to know the enemies path a predictive line will indicate which direction the enemies will follow if nothing changes. Whilst the path will be mostly obvious as it will simply be the shortest path, having a visible line will make it obvious and eliminate mistakes where the player misjudged the path.
Phases
In normal tower defence games, the waves will simply begin after a set time. The player might get time at the start to place initial towers but otherwise they have to perform building and upgrade actions whilst the waves are occuring. In this proposal I have split the game into two alternating phases, a building and a defending phase. In the building phase the player will have enough time to perform large changes to the field. This can include things like constructing complex arrangements of the towers or detailed paths for the enemies.
Building
In the building phase the player can place new towers, destroy or upgrade existing ones. They can use this time to plan and make large changes as there will be no form of time limit on these actions.
As the player will know what enemies are coming and from where, they can plan accordingly and use this information to guide their choices. The information will be available on the status screen as well as a summary on a HUD display item 
When the player is ready they will activate the Defending phase. This will be done by interacting with the central Goal.
Defending
In this phase the enemies will advance in a set of five separate waves. Each wave will occur after a specific time, regardless if all the enemies from the previous wave were killed. Whilst the player can still place and upgrade towers they will not be able to do so instantly. Each action will take time to complete. This stops the player from trapping enemies by constantly placing and removing a block. It is during this phase the the majority of the gameplay will happen. Once all five waves are over, the building phase will begin again.
The Player (and Avatar)
To avoid confusion, the player is the human controlling the game. The avatar is the in game representation of the player.
The player has three main actions they can perform. 1, building a new wall/tower. 2, Upgrading an existing tower. 3. Destroying an existing tower or wall.

The player will be obtain blocks by spending scrap, gathered from the enemies. There will be a shop style UI whereby the player can spend scrap to get new block types. This shop UI will either be in the player themselves or integrated into the goal.
The players avatar will still be bound to the same rules as it currently is in Terasology. This means the player will not have flight, infinite action range and other powerful abilities. They will be invincible as the only notable exception to this. In fact, due to the free form nature of a voxel world there is nothing stopping the player from building towers directly above the path.
The Goal
The central goal is an object that will take damage from an enemy when that enemy impacts it. In the process the enemy will be destroyed. Each enemy type will deal a set amount of damage to the goal, regardless of any stats on that particular instance of the type. Not all enemy types will deal the same amount of damage, which allows for some enemies to be more dangerous.
The goal cannot regenerate health in any way and starts with a set amount of health. This amount of health should be high enough such that at the midpoint of the game two waves of basic enemies shouldn’t manage to destroy it.
If the tower is destroyed the game is over.  The game cannot end in any other way. This does mean that the game is /technically/ not completable in any form other than by defeat. This is acceptable as the intent is to survive for as long as is possible.
After the game is finished a special game over screen will be displayed. This will contain options to recreate the world and will provide statistics and score for the player.
The Enemies
All the enemies will be instances of a limited number of types. These types will have distinctive flaws, strengths and other aspects. All enemies can be attacked by all tower types, they will simply have varying stats and special abilities. The key indication here is that they will all be instantly recognisable and the player will always know what type of enemy they are facing. Initially these models will be a placeholder. Either the gooey model recolored or some alternative asset from one of my collections.
The enemies will move directly along the shortest path from the entrance they use towards the goal. If a wall is placed or destroyed they will follow the new route, if it has changed.
When an enemy is killed they will drop scrap, a resource that is used to build and upgrade towers. The amount of scrap dropped will vary with enemy type. It is also possible to vary it with wave number, but care will be taken to prevent this from stacking with increased upgrade and build costs. The scrap will be dropped into the world, thus the player will have to actively locate and retrieve it. This will encourage interesting choices on how to structure towers so that all of the path is accessible.
In the case that there is no path that will reach the goal a special enemy unit will spawn. This will move in a direct path towards the goal until there is a path created. It will destroy any towers or walls it comes into contact with and will be invulnerable until a path is created.
After this it will be killable, but extremely hard to do so. If it manages to reach the goal it will deal massive damage. Options include a fixed amount or a fixed percentage with a minimum amount. Eg, 50% or 10 points. If the player succeeds in killing it then they will gain a very valuable reward. This prevents the player from simply blocking off any path by providing an extremely high risk for doing so.
Proposed rewards include unique blocks, upgrades to nearby blocks or simply a large amount of scrap. This should be balanced carefully so that the player has incentive to spawn it but have a catastrophic consequence if it is not killed. Making it a high risk high reward unit that the player definitely doesn’t want to accidentally spawn.
The Towers (and Walls)
(Credit for the multiblock tower idea goes to the Anonymous comment)

The other main element of the gamemode is the towers. These will be multiblock structures that attack the enemies, damaging and/or applying effects onto them. The towers will not have set shapes to be built into, rather simply a set of required blocks, leaving the exact shape up to the player. Each of the blocks will have a different function and by combining them in different ways the player can make different tower types. The ingame help will detail all the block types and provide basic example towers as a starting point
Upgrading a tower will be done by using different blocks in tower, for instance adding an Ice Core would make the tower apply a slowing effect. Replacing an Impulse Generator with a Fusion Diffuser would change the tower from single target to passive AOE. These are just examples with many more options available. This allows for both emergent gameplay and more varied tower options. It better utilises the voxel nature of Terasology.

In this image, is an example tower design. In this fictional design the red outlined glass blocks are Shell Emitters and the green outlined brick blocks are Impulse  Generators. Bullets travel from an Impulse block to the Emitter through the blue outlined Ice Core. The purple wood blocks are plain structure and the yellow Power Furnace gives the tower power. This hypothetical tower could shoot ice pellets which slow and damage an enemy.

In the left example the tower still has the Furnace in the centre and the Ice Cores, however the Impulse blocks have been switched for the green Fusion Diffusers. This tower would produce a slowing AOE effect. In this way, the player can combine blocks to produce unique towers in a predictable fashion. In this example adding an Ice Core block will create a slow effect, and using a Diffuser or Impulse block will give AOE or single target options respectively.
One block high towers or walls will not block enemies, forcing the player to think carefully about how they will create the maze and how they will access all the areas of the towers themselves. Additionally this allows for multilevel playing fields where the player can deliberately provide a one block high section for the enemies to travel in more interesting paths.
Status Screen (and other UI)
As the field is going to be large enough the payer cannot see all of it at once, HUD UI will be used to provide basic information. Additionally a status screen and an In Game Manual will give more in depth information. The main HUD elements will be; progress bar, showing the wave composition and remaining time; a health bar, the health of the goal; the current amount of scrap; and a minimap; displaying a top down view of the whole field.
The minimap will also indicate where enemies are and which towers are activated.
The status screen shows much more detailed information. It will list the stats and enemy information for each of the waves as well as having a more detailed map that shows the paths of the enemies as well as exactly which type they are.

Below is a sample mockup of the in game HUD’s. On the minimap in the top right there are current enemies, towers, entrances and the goal, in red, blue, yellow and green respectively. In the top left is the wave info, with the different fish representing different mob types. Lastly at the bottom is the current health and scrap. Obviously all the icons are placeholders and each element is subject to exact changes.

This section contains some brief points on how to implement each of the design points. These are primarily to determine how long each design point will be done, as well as to guide development. They don’t go into too deep detail, rather providing a simple example and starting point.
The Playing Field
The playing field is a section that will be constructed during the world generation section. It’s very similar to the module Structure Templates, instead occuring in the world creation steps. The primary attempt will be to convert Structure Templates to be compatible with the world generation system.

If this is not possible, instead the world generation will simply be manually hardcoded to place specific blocks at the correct position. A good suggestion for making this easier is to simply create a heightmap in a texture and use this to guide where the blocks go. This allows for much easier editing of the  playing field.
Initially the generator will be a standalone world generator, and thus cannot be used with other world generator types. It is potentially possible, with the multiple defence fields stretch goal, to change it into a plugin as the greater world would play a more significant role in that situation.

With the predictive line feature, the current ideas include: using placing physical items along the path, for instance a thin path; using the particle system to move particles along the path; implementing a RenderingSystem and using the renderOverlay method to display the path.
The player
The players shop inventory will be implemented with a few tweaks to the default one. Firstly the size will be reduced to the block count and only have the hotbar slots available. Then when an attempt to place an item is made, the event will be captured and consumed. Instead a check against the player’s scrap will be made, and then the block created.
The enemies
The enemies have two main parts, the pathfinding and the movement. Both of these will be based off the WildAnimals system. This will mean using the movement mechanics from that module and the pathfinding from the Pathfinding module. Another consideration is FlexiblePathfinding however this depends on how complete it is.. As a part of this, I may refactor sections of the movement code out of WildAnimals and into a separate module. Alternatively I shall investigate SegmentedPaths which also provides support for moving entities along a fixed path.

Unfortunately due to living in Australia, I will be at university for a portion of the program, however I feel that I am capable of participating in both GSoC and University successfully. The key issue is that I will have an exam period during the coding period of GSoC. I intend to resolve this by beginning work earlier than usual during the bonding period and by placing a higher workload in the two sections that do not straddle my exams.

I also wish to make a note that elements of the proposal may seem bare bones. This is intentional as I am aware that I am concurrently doing this and university. As such I’m potentially making the scope too small, but I am doing so with the expectation that I would be possible to complete a stretch goal.
If this is possible to do then I would know by the first evaluations, and it could be factored in to the timeline and success criteria.

Academic and Technical information
I’m a second year, studying Computer Science and Software Engineering at Monash University. This is the only formal training I’ve had and due to the nature of my degree I’ve only had units using Python so far. However I have been using Java and other programming languages for multiple years before university, which makes me confident in my ability to complete this proposal.
Contributions to MovingBlocks
So far I’ve made a number of contributions with MovingBlocks, both with code and organisational level items. I overhauled and redid the SimpleFarming module, resulting in the EdibleFlora family. I also created the BasicCrafting module and begun integration with Cooking. As my contributions so far have been mainly content focused I feel this proposal is a natural fit for my interest in Terasology
Other items include numerous engine level fixes and an inventory system overhaul which is “still in progress”. I also participated in the 2016-2017 GCI and helped run the 2017-2018 GCI.
